For Car Make¶
In [9]:
# Define a function to calculate chi-square for categorical variables
def chi_square_test(df, column, target):
    contingency_table = pd.crosstab(df[column], df[target]>df[target].median())
    chi2, p, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
    return chi2, p

# Apply chi-square test for 'car_make' and 'car_model'

chi2_car_make_freq, p_car_make_freq = chi_square_test(df, 'car_make', 'claim_freq')
chi2_car_make_amt, p_car_make_amt = chi_square_test(df, 'car_make', 'claim_amt')
chi2_car_model_freq, p_car_model_freq = chi_square_test(df, 'car_model', 'claim_freq')
chi2_car_model_amt, p_car_model_amt = chi_square_test(df, 'car_model', 'claim_amt')

print(f"Chi-square test for car make frequeny claim: chi2={chi2_car_make_freq}, p-value={p_car_make_freq}")
print(f"Chi-square test for car make amount claim: chi2={chi2_car_make_amt}, p-value={p_car_make_amt}")
print(f"Chi-square test for car model frequency claim: chi2={chi2_car_model_freq}, p-value={p_car_model_freq}")
print(f"Chi-square test for car model amount claim: chi2={chi2_car_model_amt}, p-value={p_car_model_amt}")

# Calculate the critical value

alpha = 0.05
shape = 563115
critical_value = stats.chi2.ppf(1 - alpha, shape)
print(f'Critical value for the Chi-square test = {critical_value}')

Chi-square test for car make frequeny claim: chi2=79.99070199786641, p-value=0.38532311019225357
Chi-square test for car make amount claim: chi2=91.09506115545324, p-value=0.1300698159338125
Chi-square test for car model frequency claim: chi2=1046.119708949842, p-value=0.20924088645771335
Chi-square test for car model amount claim: chi2=1038.0584158331842, p-value=0.2632355110760711
Critical value for the Chi-square test = 564861.7204906178

The Chi-square is lower than the critical value hence, there is no correlation Likewise, the p-value is higher than 0.05 hence, there is no correlation

3. What are the key characteristics of policyholders with low claim frequencies and high household incomes?¶

In [10]:
# Define thresholds
low_claim_freq_threshold = df['claim_freq'].quantile(0.25)
high_income_threshold = df['household_income'].quantile(0.75)

# Filter policyholders with low claim frequencies and high household incomes
low_claim_high_income = df[(df['claim_freq'] <= low_claim_freq_threshold) & (df['household_income'] >= high_income_threshold)]


# Distribution of key categorical characteristics
categorical_vars = ['marital_status', 'car_use', 'gender', 'parent', 'education', 'car_make', 'car_model', 'car_color', 
                    'coverage_zone']

for var in categorical_vars:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.countplot(x=low_claim_high_income[var])
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {var} among Policyholders with Low Claim Frequency and High Income')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.show()

# Distribution of key numerical characteristics
numerical_vars = ['kids_driving', 'car_year']

for var in numerical_vars:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(low_claim_high_income[var], bins=30, kde=True)
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {var} among Policyholders with Low Claim Frequency and High Income')
    plt.show()

The percentage distribution were the same with the descriptive statistics except for coverage zone where highly rural has a higher percentage.

8. How does the presence of children driving affect the frequency and number of claims?¶

In [33]:
# T-test for claim frequency

from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# Separate data into groups
group_with_kids = df[df['kids_driving'] > 0]['claim_freq']
group_without_kids = df[df['kids_driving'] == 0]['claim_freq']

# Perform t-test
t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(group_with_kids, group_without_kids)
print(f'T-test for Claim Frequency: t-statistic = {t_stat}, p-value = {p_value}')


#Critical value
n1 = (df['kids_driving'] > 0).sum()
n2 = (df['kids_driving'] == 0).sum()
alpha = 0.05
dof = n1 + n2 - 2
critical_value = stats.t.ppf(1 - alpha / 2, dof)
print(f'The critical value for the t-test at alpha = {alpha} and dof = {dof} is: {critical_value}')

T-test for Claim Frequency: t-statistic = -0.49813375766910983, p-value = 0.6183926865748199
The critical value for the t-test at alpha = 0.05 and dof = 37540 is: 1.9600271797030413

The t-test for claim frequency shows that the presence of kids does not affect the claim frequeny

#T-test for claim amount

# Separate data into groups
group_with_kids_amt = df[df['kids_driving'] > 0]['claim_amt']
group_without_kids_amt = df[df['kids_driving'] == 0]['claim_amt']

# Perform t-test
t_stat_amt, p_value_amt = ttest_ind(group_with_kids_amt, group_without_kids_amt)
print(f'T-test for Claim Amount: t-statistic = {t_stat_amt}, p-value = {p_value_amt}')

#Critical value
n1 = (df['kids_driving'] > 0).sum()
n2 = (df['kids_driving'] == 0).sum()
alpha = 0.05
dof = n1 + n2 - 2
critical_value = stats.t.ppf(1 - alpha / 2, dof)
print(f'The critical value for the t-test at alpha = {alpha} and dof = {dof} is: {critical_value}')

T-test for Claim Amount: t-statistic = -0.8362472799449246, p-value = 0.40302112787337296
The critical value for the t-test at alpha = 0.05 and dof = 37540 is: 1.9600271797030413

The t-test for claim amount shows that the presence of kids does not affect the claim amount
